Here are both approaches for MAUI Shell navigation with `IQueryAttributable`:

**1. Register the route (AppShell.xaml.cs)**
```csharp
Routing.RegisterRoute("ProductDetailsPage", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate from ProductListPage**
```csharp
// Approach A: Pass product ID as a simple string query parameter
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"ProductDetailsPage?productId={product.Id}");

// Approach B: Pass the full Product object via a dictionary
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("ProductDetailsPage", new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", selectedProduct }
});
```

**3. Receive data in the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`**
```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private readonly IProductService _productService;

    public Product Product { get; private set; }

    public ProductDetailsViewModel(IProductService productService)
    {
        _productService = productService;
    }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach B: full object passed via navigation dictionary
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            Product = product;
        }
        // Approach A: only the ID was passed as a query string
        else if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string id = idObj.ToString();
            Product = _productService.GetProduct(id);
        }
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String query param | Dictionary object |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | `$"route?key={val}"` | `GoToAsync(route, dict)` |
| **Type received** | `string` (always) | Original object type |
| **Deep-link / URL safe** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| **Complex objects** | Needs a lookup/service | ✅ Direct |

The `ApplyQueryAttributes` method is called automatically by Shell when the page resolves its `BindingContext` — no `[QueryProperty]` attributes needed. This single entry point handles both navigation styles cleanly.
